In this press conference, President Obama discusses the comprehensive deal that was achieved with Iran to prevent them from obtaining a nuclear weapon. He emphasizes the importance of the American people and Congress having the opportunity to review the deal and highlights the benefits of the agreement. He explains that the deal cuts off Iran's pathways to a nuclear weapons program, includes extensive monitoring and verification measures, and has consequences for Iran if they violate their commitments. The President also acknowledges that there are still differences and concerns with Iran's behavior in areas such as support for terrorism, but emphasizes that this deal is focused on preventing a nuclear weapon. He addresses some criticisms and questions, including concerns about Iran's use of the money they will receive from sanctions relief, the effectiveness of inspections, and the potential for Iran to pursue a nuclear weapon in the future. He defends the deal and argues that it is the best way to prevent Iran from obtaining a nuclear weapon.